   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_696_1818-08-24_letter01_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <dateline>
                  <name type="place" ref="Id_where"/>
                  <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Nelson-Place-2_ENK">2 Nelson Place Bath</placeName>
                  <date when="1818-08-24">Aug<hi rend="superscript">st</hi>. 24<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. 1818</date>
               </dateline>
               <salute>
                  <persName>Dearest <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">mother</persName>
                  </persName>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>
               Every one of<lb/>
               the letters which you so very<lb/>
               kindly wrote to us reached<lb/>
               us yesterday - <hi rend="underline">Thank you</hi>
               <lb/>
               I cannot express how much<lb/>
               I feel obliged by your writing<lb/>
               all this in your situation<lb/>
               - However dreadful the <choice>
                  <orig>de-<lb/>
               tails</orig>
                  <reg>details</reg>
               </choice> there is a sort of <choice>
                  <orig>satisfac<lb/>
               tion</orig>
                  <reg>satisfaction</reg>
               </choice> in knowing the truth<lb/>
               &amp; being relieved from suspense<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               - do you say the best we<lb/>
               can now hope is that this<lb/>
               noble creature may not <choice>
                  <orig>sur<lb/>
               vive</orig>
                  <reg>survive</reg>
               </choice> the loss of all that <choice>
                  <orig>dis-<lb/>
               tinguished</orig>
                  <reg>distinguished</reg>
               </choice> him among men<lb/>
               &amp; that he may without more<lb/>
               suffering breathe his last -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               - You surely cannot doubt<lb/>
               that we should think you<lb/>
               did right in sending the<lb/>
               young ones to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Castleforbes_IE">Castle Forbes</placeName>
               <lb/>
               - nothing could be better<lb/>
               - God bless <persName ref="./Personography.xml#GranX1">Lady G</persName> - You have<lb/>
               a great comfort even in these<lb/>
               terrible circumstances in<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_696_1818-08-24_letter01_page02.jpg"/>
               feeling <hi rend="underline">sure</hi> that wherever<lb/>
               your daughters &amp; sons are<lb/>
               they are in all that depends<lb/>
               on their own conduct safe -<lb/>
               and must do you credit<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeH4">Honora</persName> seemed to enjoy<lb/>
               her journey &amp; the open carriage<lb/>
               - fine weather and change<lb/>
               of scene more even than you<lb/>
               could possibly have expected<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               - Her mind is admirably<lb/>
               calm - &amp; more easily amused<lb/>
               than my own - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeA2">Anna</persName> is<lb/>
               as you well know all kind<lb/>
               ness - and she has such delight<lb/>
               ful soft manners <del>ha</del>
               <lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeH4">Honora</persName> had such a headache<lb/>
               yesterday (the only one she has<lb/>
               had since we left <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Black-Castle_IE">Black Castle</placeName>)<lb/>
               that I was glad we had not<lb/>
               received an answer to a note<lb/>
               I wrote Em. to say we <choice>
                  <orig>w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>.</orig>
                  <reg>would</reg>
               </choice> go there<lb/>
               yesterday - we have heard<lb/>
               from her to day - a very kind<lb/>
               note -. In an hours time we<lb/>
               are going - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeH4">Honora's</persName> head pretty<lb/>
               well - as soon as I see how<lb/>
               things are at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Clifton_ENK">Clifton</placeName> I will write<lb/>
               to you again - I have read your<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_696_1818-08-24_letter01_page03.jpg"/>
               letter to Aunt C - and will <choice>
                  <orig>deli<lb/>
               ver</orig>
                  <reg>deliver</reg>
               </choice> it as I think her mind<lb/>
               is strong enough to bear the<lb/>
               truth and it must come<lb/>
               sooner or later - The shock might<lb/>
               be much worse if it came all<lb/>
               at once -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               I did not receive from <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LittX1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>.<lb/>
               Little</persName>
               <hi rend="underline">the Bond</hi> - so I shall say<lb/>
               nothing of business &amp; hope <choice>
                  <orig>no-<lb/>
               thing</orig>
                  <reg>nothing</reg>
               </choice> will be said to me - If<lb/>
               the subject is touched upon I shall<lb/>
               say that <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeL2">Lovell</persName> &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeC1">Sneyd</persName> had<lb/>
               ordered a bond to be drawn<lb/>
               but that it was not ready -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               We shall stay till Thursday<lb/>
               I think - We have desired<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeA2">Anna</persName> to forward any Irish<lb/>
               letters to us - as we <hi rend="underline">live</hi> upon<lb/>
               your letters - My dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName>
               <lb/>
               wrote to me from <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Castleforbes_IE">Castle Forbes</placeName>
               <lb/>
               so we know every thing about<lb/>
               you all as if we were with<lb/>
               you - I hope my dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">mother</persName>
               <lb/>
               you continue to think <del>I</del> we<lb/>
               did right <del>
                  <unclear/>
               </del> in <choice>
                  <orig>com-<lb/>
                  ing</orig>
                  <reg>coming</reg>
               </choice> to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#ENK">England</placeName> - If you wished<lb/>
               for us back again say but the<lb/>
               word and we will come at<lb/>
               any time - Thank God you will<lb/>
               tell me the truth -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               This morning I read a most kind<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_696_1818-08-24_letter01_page04.jpg"/>
               letter from <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LansL1">Lady Lansdowne</persName>
               <lb/>
               begging us to come to her as<lb/>
               soon as possible - I shall not<lb/>
               answer till we have seen my<lb/>
               aunts - I think it would be<lb/>
               dreadful to go into <hi rend="underline">company</hi>
               <lb/>
               at present - and could not answer<lb/>
               any purpose for <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeH4">Honora</persName> - nor<lb/>
               could it be even proper - <choice>
                  <orig>There-<lb/>
               fore</orig>
                  <reg>Therefore</reg>
               </choice> I wish to put off the visit -<lb/>
               <del>I will write</del> As soon as I get to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Clifton_ENK">Clifton</placeName>
               <lb/>
               &amp; hear what my aunts say - I will<lb/>
               write to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LansL1">Lady L</persName>- and to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DumoE1">Dumont</persName>
               <lb/>
               - I will tell <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LansL1">Lady L</persName> my brother<lb/>
               is exceedingly ill - that we do<lb/>
               not wish &amp;c - &amp; I will write to<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DumoE1">D-</persName> to ask if he can now read the<lb/>
               M<hi rend="superscript">s</hi>. <add>I will send it to him</add> &amp; if I <hi rend="underline">can</hi> see him in <choice>
                  <orig>Nov<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>.</orig>
                  <reg>November</reg>
               </choice>
               <lb/>
               or if he stays at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Bowood-House_ENK">Bowood</placeName> suppose<lb/>
               in Sep<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>.? <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeA2">Anna</persName> asks us to stay<lb/>
               here a fortnight &amp; promises she<lb/>
               will let no company in - that<lb/>
               she will say at once W. has a<lb/>
               fever &amp; that is sufficient answer<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#FitzC2">Lady C Fitzgerald</persName> has been<lb/>
               exceedingly kind - She has been<lb/>
               here twice - has this moment<lb/>
               shewn me a letter from <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LansL1">Lady G</persName>
               <lb/>
               saying she never pitied a creatures<lb/>
               so much in her life as she does<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName> &amp; you - that <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">F</persName> is the picture<lb/>
               of pale grief - She speaks with great<lb/>
               fondness <add>&amp; admiration</add> of P. &amp; F- -&amp; says they are<lb/>
               not the slightest trouble - to E's state<lb/>
               she says is hopeless but no <hi rend="underline">danger of death</hi>.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <pb n="5" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_696_1818-08-24_letter01_page05.jpg"/>
               - I wrote to your ex brother &amp; have had<lb/>
               a most touchingly kind letter from<lb/>
               him - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BailM1">D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Baillie</persName> is very ill &amp; I have<lb/>
               fears that this will prevent our<lb/>
               scheme of being with <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BailJ1">Joanna Baillie</persName>
               <lb/>
               - I shall write to her from <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Clifton_ENK">Clifton</placeName> -<lb/>
               - I have had a kind letter from <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HopeT1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Hope</persName>
               <lb/>
               wishing to see us -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               I beg you will write one line &amp; not<lb/>
               more dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">mother</persName> to tell me <choice>
                  <orig>whe-<lb/>
               ther</orig>
                  <reg>whether</reg>
               </choice> you approve of what I propose<lb/>
               doing - I assure you I command me<lb/>
               <unclear/>ind &amp; am as calm as possible -<lb/>
               But your approbation is necessary<lb/>
               to me -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#CramX1">Crampton</persName> promised to write to<lb/>
               Post Office <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Shrewsbury_ENK">Shrewsbury</placeName> but I suppose<lb/>
               he had nothing to say - We have not<lb/>
               heard from him - I wonder he<lb/>
               has not gone down to you<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeA2">Anna's</persName> love -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               Give my most affectionate love &amp;<lb/>
               admiration to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeL2">Lovell</persName> -<lb/>
            </p>
            <closer>
               I am dearest <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">mother</persName>
               <lb/>
            </closer>
            <closer>
               <pb n="6" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_696_1818-08-24_letter01_page06.jpg"/>
               <address>
                  <addrLine>
                     <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria</persName>
                  </addrLine>
                  <lb/>
                  <addrLine>24 August</addrLine>
                  <lb/>
                  <addrLine>1818</addrLine>
                  <lb/>
                  <addrLine>34 - 8 - 5</addrLine>
                  <lb/>
                  <addrLine>
                     <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Edgeworth</persName>
                  </addrLine>
                  <lb/>
                  <addrLine>
                     <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE">Edgeworthstown</placeName>.</addrLine>
                  <lb/>
               </address>
            </closer>
         </div>
      </body>
